<subSubSection id="C320655BFFDFFFA9BE76FDE5FD5A3C81" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8536D0FFDFFFA9BE76FDE5FB863B66" blockId="9.[113,1090,515,1596]" box="[113,1090,515,540]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis id="B94EEAC2FFDFFFA9BE76FDE5FF3F3B66" bold="true" box="[113,251,515,539]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">Description.</emphasis>
Body length: males 5.25-6.10 mm (
<typeStatus id="54818872FFDFFFA9BC72FDE2FD173B61" box="[629,723,516,540]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">holotype</typeStatus>
<quantity id="4CC29B35FFDFFFA9BCDEFDE2FCF83B61" box="[729,828,516,540]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.6" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" unit="mm" value="5.6">5.60 mm</quantity>
); females 6.00- 
<quantity id="4CC29B35FFDFFFA9BDDBFDE2FBFA3B66" box="[988,1086,516,540]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.85" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" unit="mm" value="6.85">6.85 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8536D0FFDFFFA9BE97FDC2FC3F3A61" blockId="9.[113,1090,515,1596]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">Male: Body flattened, parallel, densely pubescent and dull. Head yellow, vertex with one large black spot not touching inner margin of eyes, postgenae black posteriorly, apices of mandibles darkened. Antennae yellow, in some specimens with infuscate apices of last five segments. Pronotum yellow with three black spots (one median and two lateral). Scutellum black, elytra metallic green. Prosternum yellow with darkened anterior margin. Mesosternum yellow with large black median spot, mesoepisternum black, mesoepimera yellow. Metasternum black with paler posterior margin, metaepisternum yellow.Abdomen dark brown to black, last ventrite with yellow posterior margin. Legs yellow, last two tarsomeres infuscate.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8536D0FFDFFFA9BE97FCC2FD813AA1" blockId="9.[113,1090,515,1596]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">Labrum transverse, laterally covered with several pale setae, anterior margin slightly sinuate. Anterior part of head semiopaque, sparsely covered with pale setae. Frontal tubercles small, subtriangular, covered with microsculpture, semiopaque. Vertex dull, with large feeble groove behind frontal tubercles, coarsely and densely punctate and covered with short pale hairs. Antennae filiform, 0.75 times as long as body, length ratio of antennomeres 1 to 11 equal to 17-8-15-23-19-17-16-16-14-13-16.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8536D0FFDFFFA9BE97FC02FE1C3DE6" blockId="9.[113,1090,515,1596]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">Pronotum tranverse, 1. 95 times as broad as long, widest at anterior third, narrowed posteriad, semiopaque, densely covered with coarse punctures and pale hairs. Surface with two large lateral depressions.Anterior margin widely shallowly concave, posterior margin straight. Anterior and posterior margins thinly bordered, lateral margins indistinctly bordered. Anteri- or angles widely rounded, with distinct small teeth, posterior angles obtusely angulate, all angles bearing one long pale seta.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8536D0FFDFFFA9BE97FB42FCE53C66" blockId="9.[113,1090,515,1596]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">Scutellum subtriangular with rounded apex, densely covered with small punctures and short pale hairs, semiopaque. Elytra parallel and dull. Humeral calli well developed. Elytral surface very densely covered with small confluent punctures and short pale hairs. Epipleura distinct but narrow, disappearing before the apex. Macropterous.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8536D0FFDFFFA9BE97FAC2FE193C21" blockId="9.[113,1090,515,1596]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">Ventral surface lustrous, finely punctate and covered with pale hairs. Last visible ventrite with deep subtrapezoidal incision.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8536D0FFDFFFA9BE97FA82FDAF3CE1" blockId="9.[113,1090,515,1596]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">
Hind tarsomere 1 1.15 times as long as following two tarsomeres combined. Middle and hind tarsomeres 1 robust (
<figureCitation id="13012A55FFDFFFA9BF81FA62FE103CE1" box="[390,468,1412,1436]" captionStart-0="Figs 1-5" captionStart-1="Figs" captionStart-2="Figs" captionStartId-0="2.[151,187,1077,1096]" captionStartId-1="4.[151,190,1164,1183]" captionStartId-2="5.[113,152,1508,1527]" captionTargetBox-0="[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetBox-1="[185,1092,220,1131]" captionTargetBox-2="[140,1057,583,1477]" captionTargetId-0="figure-241@2.[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetId-1="figure-136@4.[185,1092,220,1131]" captionTargetId-2="figure-126@5.[140,1057,583,1477]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="4" captionTargetPageId-2="5" captionText-0="Figs 1-5. Apophylia nobilitata Gerstaecker, 1871. 1 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 2 – last ventrite of female; 3 – last ventrite and pygidium of female, lateral view; 4 – male metasternum; 5 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs 1-3 and 5); 2 mm (Fig. 4)." captionText-1="Figs. 6-8. Apophylia vernallis (Allard, 1889). 6 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 7 – last ventrite of female; 8 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm." captionText-2="Figs. 9-13. Apophylia mila sp. nov. 9 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 10 – last ventrite of female; 11 – last ventrite and pygidium of female (lateral view); 12 – male metasternum; 13 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs. 9-11 and 13); 2 mm (Fig. 12)." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174140" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174142" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174144" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5174140/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5174142/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/5174144/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
). Claws bifid.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8536D0FFDFFFA9BE97FA42FE223CC6" blockId="9.[113,1090,515,1596]" box="[144,486,1444,1468]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">
Shape of aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation id="13012A55FFDFFFA9BF93FA42FE263CC6" box="[404,482,1444,1468]" captionStart-0="Figs 1-5" captionStart-1="Figs" captionStartId-0="2.[151,187,1077,1096]" captionStartId-1="4.[151,190,1164,1183]" captionTargetBox-0="[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetBox-1="[185,1092,220,1131]" captionTargetId-0="figure-241@2.[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetId-1="figure-136@4.[185,1092,220,1131]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="4" captionText-0="Figs 1-5. Apophylia nobilitata Gerstaecker, 1871. 1 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 2 – last ventrite of female; 3 – last ventrite and pygidium of female, lateral view; 4 – male metasternum; 5 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs 1-3 and 5); 2 mm (Fig. 4)." captionText-1="Figs. 6-8. Apophylia vernallis (Allard, 1889). 6 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 7 – last ventrite of female; 8 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174140" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174142" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5174140/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5174142/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8536D0FFDFFFA9BE97FA22FD5A3C81" blockId="9.[113,1090,515,1596]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">
Female: Abdomen yellow. Last ventrite with small semicircular incision (
<figureCitation id="13012A55FFDFFFA9BD93FA22FC253CA1" box="[916,993,1476,1500]" captionStart-0="Figs 1-5" captionStart-1="Figs" captionStartId-0="2.[151,187,1077,1096]" captionStartId-1="4.[151,190,1164,1183]" captionTargetBox-0="[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetBox-1="[185,1092,220,1131]" captionTargetId-0="figure-241@2.[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetId-1="figure-136@4.[185,1092,220,1131]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="4" captionText-0="Figs 1-5. Apophylia nobilitata Gerstaecker, 1871. 1 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 2 – last ventrite of female; 3 – last ventrite and pygidium of female, lateral view; 4 – male metasternum; 5 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs 1-3 and 5); 2 mm (Fig. 4)." captionText-1="Figs. 6-8. Apophylia vernallis (Allard, 1889). 6 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 7 – last ventrite of female; 8 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174140" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174142" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5174140/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5174142/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
). Middle and hind tarsomeres 1 slender. Claws appendiculate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C320655BFFDFFFAABE76F9E5FBC03DCF" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B8536D0FFDFFFAABE76F9E5FBC03DCF" blockId="9.[113,1090,515,1596]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1127,1146,1330]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis id="B94EEAC2FFDFFFA9BE76F9E5FEAC3F66" bold="true" box="[113,360,1539,1563]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C3A4D53FFDFFFA9BF6AF9E2FDD03F61" authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" box="[365,532,1540,1564]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kaffa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94EEAC2FFDFFFA9BF6AF9E2FDD03F61" box="[365,532,1540,1564]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">Apophylia kaffa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27D57B9FFDFFFA9BC1FF9E2FDAD3F66" box="[536,617,1540,1563]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A4D53FFDFFFA9BD26F9E2FC603F61" authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" box="[801,932,1540,1564]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cervenkai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94EEAC2FFDFFFA9BD26F9E2FC603F61" box="[801,932,1540,1564]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">A. cervenkai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27D57B9FFDFFFA9BDAEF9E2FC3E3F66" box="[937,1018,1540,1563]" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A4D53FFDFFFA9BA2DF9E2FF093F41" baseAuthorityName="Allard" baseAuthorityYear="1889" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vernallis">
<emphasis id="B94EEAC2FFDFFFA9BA2DF9E2FF093F41" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="74">A. vernallis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. All three species can be clearly separated only by the shapes of the aedeagi. The aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A4D53FFDCFFAABF1BFB9CFEAB3DEF" authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" box="[284,367,1146,1170]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kaffa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94EEAC2FFDCFFAABF1BFB9CFEAB3DEF" box="[284,367,1146,1170]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">A. kaffa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27D57B9FFDCFFAABF71FB9CFE0D3DEC" box="[374,457,1146,1169]" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is very thin and symmetrical (
<figureCitation id="13012A55FFDCFFAABD09FB9CFC983DEF" box="[782,860,1146,1170]" captionStart-0="Figs 1-5" captionStart-1="Figs" captionStartId-0="2.[151,187,1077,1096]" captionStartId-1="4.[151,190,1164,1183]" captionTargetBox-0="[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetBox-1="[185,1092,220,1131]" captionTargetId-0="figure-241@2.[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetId-1="figure-136@4.[185,1092,220,1131]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="4" captionText-0="Figs 1-5. Apophylia nobilitata Gerstaecker, 1871. 1 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 2 – last ventrite of female; 3 – last ventrite and pygidium of female, lateral view; 4 – male metasternum; 5 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs 1-3 and 5); 2 mm (Fig. 4)." captionText-1="Figs. 6-8. Apophylia vernallis (Allard, 1889). 6 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 7 – last ventrite of female; 8 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174140" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174142" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5174140/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5174142/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
), while the aedeagi of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A4D53FFDCFFAABA57FB9CFF3A3DCF" authority="Bezděk, 2005" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2005" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cervenkai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94EEAC2FFDCFFAABA57FB9CFF3A3DCF" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">A. cervenkai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27D57B9FFDCFFAABF02FB7CFE933DCC" box="[261,343,1178,1201]" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A4D53FFDCFFAABF8CFB7CFDC13DCF" baseAuthorityName="Allard" baseAuthorityYear="1889" box="[395,517,1178,1202]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Apophylia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vernallis">
<emphasis id="B94EEAC2FFDCFFAABF8CFB7CFDC13DCF" box="[395,517,1178,1202]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">A. vernallis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are more robust and asymmetrical (
<figureCitation id="13012A55FFDCFFAABD83FB7CFC0B3DCC" box="[900,975,1177,1202]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="4.[151,190,1164,1183]" captionTargetBox="[185,1092,220,1131]" captionTargetId="figure-136@4.[185,1092,220,1131]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs. 6-8. Apophylia vernallis (Allard, 1889). 6 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 7 – last ventrite of female; 8 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174142" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174142/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13012A55FFDCFFAABDDDFB7CFC333DCF" box="[986,1015,1178,1202]" captionStart="Figs 1-5" captionStartId="2.[151,187,1077,1096]" captionTargetBox="[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetId="figure-241@2.[185,1092,220,1046]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs 1-5. Apophylia nobilitata Gerstaecker, 1871. 1 – aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view); 2 – last ventrite of female; 3 – last ventrite and pygidium of female, lateral view; 4 – male metasternum; 5 – male metatarsus. Scale: 1 mm (Figs 1-3 and 5); 2 mm (Fig. 4)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174140" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174140/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="75">14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
